# 10_subtitle_demo — s191 subtitle support proof.
#
# Lines starting `#[sub]` render in two places at once:
#
#   1. The Scripter output pane gets a flanked caption (── text ──)
#      with blank lines either side. Useful when reading the trace.
#   2. MainWindow's caption bar (above the status bar) shows the
#      text in a large readable banner. That's where the user's
#      eyes are while they watch Curvz drive itself.
#
# Plain `#` lines stay comment-skip, so the file-header docstring
# at the top of every script keeps its meaning. The marker is
# opt-in. The bracketed-tag shape (`#[sub]`, future `#[chapter]`,
# etc.) is a small extensible DSL — unknown tags are skipped, so
# scripts using future tags stay forward-compatible.
#
# Pacing: after a `#[sub]` line the next-line delay is doubled, so
# the caption sits visible for 2× the user's step-delay setting
# before the next verb dispatches. Set the Step delay spin button
# to 300–500ms before Running and the captions arrive at reading
# speed. (At step delay 0 — "no pacing" — captions fly past with
# everything else; the user opted out of pacing.)

#[sub] Let's walk three toolbar tools

tb_sel click
assert tb_sel active == true

#[sub] Now switch to the Node tool

tb_nod click
assert tb_nod active == true
assert tb_sel active == false

#[sub] Finally, the Pen tool

tb_pen click
assert tb_pen active == true
assert tb_nod active == false

#[sub] Done. Three tools clicked, radio invariant held throughout.
